At least, recur to nature, which, in confirmation of the faith for our best teaching, continually produces and gives birth to new animals, without union of male and female.
The first crea­ ture was begotten of clay;
this last is engendered of wood.
The one, proceeding from the God of nature for once only, was a stupendous miracle;
the other, though not less ad­ mirable, is less to be wondered at, because imitative nature often performs it.
But human nature is so constituted, that it holds nothing to be precious and admirable but what is uncommon and of rare occurrence.
The rising and setting of the sun, than which there is nothing in the world more beautiful, nothing more fit to excite our wonder, we pass by without any admiration, because they are daily presented to our eyes;
while an eclipse of the sun fills the whole world with astonishment, because it rarely occurs.
