THERE were no archbishops in Ireland, but the bishops con­ secrated each other mutually, until John Papyrio came as legate from the see of Rome not many years ago.3
He brought four palls to Ireland, one of which he conferred on Armagh;
another he gave to Dublin, where Gregory was then bishop ;
the third to Cashel;
the fourth to Tuam (Toe­ niam), in Connaught.
St. Patrick died and rested in the Lord in the one hundred and twentieth year of his age, in the year of our Lord 485, and from the arrival of the Irish 1800.
